Passkeys: the next step on your passwordless journey
We’re excited to announce that passkeys are now available in beta for our LastPass Free and Premium customers – that’s you, through your desktop on Chrome!
New to passkeys?
A passkey is a way to log in to apps and websites without using a traditional username and password. Instead, it uses a pair of keys: a public key and a private key. 
 
The public key is stored by the app or website, and the private key is stored in LastPass. Simply put, when combined, this unique key pair grants secure access. 
 
Passkeys leverage cryptography to prevent unauthorized access and securely authenticate users. They are phishing-resistant, making them one of the safest login methods. Additionally, passkeys are incredibly convenient since you never need to remember them. In fact, you don’t even see them!
Getting Started
Turn on the passkey beta feature. Here’s how:
•
Open Account Settings in the vault.
•
Find General Tab > Beta Features > Passkeys: Save and use passkeys.
•
Click Update on the bottom and enter your master password to verify it’s you.
•
Close and reopen the Chrome browser before adding your first passkey.
•
Use the LastPass extension in Chrome to create, save, and log in with passkeys on sites that support them.
Helpful Hints
As with any emerging technology, you might come across a few bumps in the road. Here are some helpful hints and reminders:
•
Both the app/website and the password manager need to support passkeys for you to create and use a passkey. Since this technology is new and evolving, not all apps/websites support passkeys yet!
•
This is a beta – we want your feedback. You can submit feedback directly by clicking “Report a problem” in the LastPass extension.
